  <content>
    <title>Trade-off Communication and Documentation</title>

    <summary>Architecture trade-offs must be communicated differently to executives, product managers, engineers, and operations. Every significant decision requires structured documentation covering context, evaluated options, criteria and weights, identified trade-offs, risks and mitigations, and decision rationale. Stakeholder surprise — trade-offs discovered in production — is the most costly failure mode.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Poor stakeholder communication causes misaligned expectations and resistance to change. Undocumented trade-offs lead to "decision amnesia" — teams revisiting settled debates when the original decision-makers leave or context is lost. Ignored quality attributes cause systems to fail NFRs in production. Structured communication by audience ensures each group hears the trade-offs in terms that matter to them, enabling informed approval rather than surprised escalation after implementation.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Writing the "Consequences" section of any ADR — to enumerate explicit gain/loss pairs.</item>
        <item>Presenting a technology or architecture decision to non-technical stakeholders (executives, product).</item>
        <item>Generating an ADR from a decision matrix or ATAM analysis.</item>
        <item>Stakeholder review before committing to a Type-1 irreversible decision.</item>
        <item>Post-implementation review — communicating whether predicted trade-offs materialized.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Type-2 reversible small-scope decisions — a brief ADR comment is sufficient; full stakeholder communication creates noise.</item>
        <item>When stakeholders have not been identified yet — agents will invent generic personas and the output looks plausible but binds nobody.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="audience-mapping">
      <p>Communicate the same decision differently depending on audience. What matters and what to avoid:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Executives — focus on: business impact, cost, risk. Avoid: technical details, implementation specifics.</item>
        <item>Product — focus on: user impact, timeline, feature implications. Avoid: implementation complexity, technical debt.</item>
        <item>Engineering — focus on: technical trade-offs, implementation approach, quality attributes. Avoid: business justification (they know it).</item>
        <item>Operations — focus on: operational impact, SLAs, monitoring and alerting changes, runbook updates. Avoid: feature details.</item>
      </list>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every stakeholder communication about a trade-off MUST preserve the key risk, even when simplifying for a non-technical audience. Verify the executive summary by asking: "Does this summary allow the executive to understand what they are approving and what could go wrong?" If no, rewrite.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents drop nuance for executives, producing clean summaries that omit the downsides. When the downside materializes, executives feel misled. The communication must be simple but complete on risks — complexity can be omitted, risk cannot.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="communication-tactics">
      <p>Communication tactics for non-technical stakeholders:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Use visual representations (tables, comparison matrices, risk heat maps) instead of prose for non-technical stakeholders.</item>
        <item>Use business terms (cost, risk, timeline, revenue impact) over technical terms (latency, throughput, ACID).</item>
        <item>Decision matrices show objective comparison — display them to stakeholders to demonstrate rigor.</item>
        <item>Risk heat maps communicate severity — two axes (probability, impact) with color coding.</item>
        <item>ADR readout meetings: 10-15 minutes of silent reading of the ADR, then discussion. This forces all attendees to engage with the actual content before the meeting becomes dominated by whoever speaks first.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="documentation-requirements">
      <p>Every significant trade-off decision MUST be documented with these six elements:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Context: what prompted this decision?</item>
        <item>Options evaluated: all alternatives considered, including "do nothing".</item>
        <item>Criteria and weights: how options were scored and who validated the weights.</item>
        <item>Trade-offs identified: what we gain and what we lose with the chosen option.</item>
        <item>Risks and mitigations: how we address the downsides of the chosen option.</item>
        <item>Decision rationale: why this option despite its trade-offs.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Capture the criteria you considered and rejected — future readers learn as much from rejected criteria as from accepted ones. Tag every ADR with the quality attributes it touches so the architect skill can cross-reference related decisions.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="ADR generation from decision">
<![CDATA[Generate an Architecture Decision Record for:

Decision: [What we're deciding]
Context: [Why we're making this decision now]

Options considered:
1. [Option A]: [Brief description]
2. [Option B]: [Brief description]
3. [Option C]: [Brief description]

Our choice: [Option X]

Generate a complete ADR with:
- Context (expanded)
- Decision drivers
- Options with pros/cons
- Decision outcome
- Trade-offs accepted (what we gain AND lose)
- Consequences (positive, negative, neutral)
- Risks and mitigations

Use a professional but concise tone. Focus on capturing the "why" not just the "what".]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="stakeholder translation">
<![CDATA[Translate this technical trade-off decision for [audience: executives/product/operations]:

Technical decision: [Description with technical terms]
Trade-offs: [Technical trade-offs]

Rewrite for [audience] focusing on:
- Business impact (cost, timeline, risk)
- What changes for them
- What they need to approve/support
- Simple analogy if helpful

Format as a 1-page summary with:
- The Question (1 sentence)
- Options (simple comparison)
- Recommendation (with business rationale)
- Trade-offs (in business terms)
- Ask (what you need from them)]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="decision review for blind spots">
<![CDATA[Review this trade-off decision for blind spots:

Decision: [What was decided]
Context: [When and why]
Options considered: [List]
Chosen option: [Selection]
Stated trade-offs: [What we documented]

Act as a critical reviewer and identify:
1. Trade-offs we may have missed
2. Risks not adequately addressed
3. Assumptions that might not hold
4. Alternative options not considered
5. Questions we should have asked but did not

Be constructively critical — help us make a better decision.]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="full analysis session chain">
<![CDATA[Session structure for a full trade-off analysis (use prompts in sequence):

PROMPT 1: "What decision do I need to make? Clarify the decision scope for [problem]."
PROMPT 2: "Generate options for [clarified decision]. Include at least one unconventional option."
PROMPT 3: "Create evaluation criteria for choosing between [options] in context of [constraints]."
PROMPT 4: "Analyze trade-offs between [shortlisted options] using [criteria]."
PROMPT 5: "Identify risks for [top option] and suggest mitigations."
PROMPT 6: "Generate an ADR documenting this decision including trade-offs."
PROMPT 7: "Review the ADR for blind spots and missing considerations."]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="anti-patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Stakeholder surprise: trade-offs discovered in production by stakeholders who were not informed during the decision.</description>
        <reason>Late discovery of trade-offs creates distrust and triggers retroactive debates about a decision that is already implemented. Early stakeholder involvement at the decision point is cheaper than production incident management.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Hidden trade-offs: not documenting what we sacrifice with the chosen option in the ADR.</description>
        <reason>Future architects assume the current implementation is the optimal one, not an explicit trade-off. Without the documented sacrifice, the next person adds more complexity on top instead of understanding why the simpler approach was chosen.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Letting one agent both generate options and write the stakeholder summary — without a separate review pass for completeness.</description>
        <reason>When stakeholder-rendering, agents drop nuance for executives. The agent that generated the technical analysis is not a reliable editor of its own output. A separate review prompt ("does this summary preserve the key risk?") catches losses.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Tooling for trade-off analysis documentation:</p>
      <list>
        <item>adr-tools — Bash CLI to scaffold ADRs (`adr new "Pick database"`). https://github.com/npryce/adr-tools</item>
        <item>log4brains — ADR static site generator with diff/history. `npm i -g log4brains`</item>
        <item>dasel / yq — Edit YAML/JSON criteria matrices in scripted agent loops. `brew install dasel`</item>
        <item>pandoc — Render ADR plus matrix to PDF for stakeholder distribution. `apt install pandoc`</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli — Render utility trees and decision trees to SVG. `npm i -g @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli`</item>
        <item>gh — Open PR with ADR draft, request review from quality attribute owners. https://cli.github.com/</item>
        <item>Structurizr — SaaS/OSS DSL-driven; agent can author decision records alongside C4 model.</item>
        <item>Backstage TechDocs — OSS, Markdown ADRs render natively; pairs with adr-tools.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

